         <div>
            <head>
               <title>Introduction</title>
            </head>            
            <p>Maass first edited the text from the <ref type="altMs" target="StGall_250.xml">St. Gall Ms 250</ref> (s. IX<hi rend="sup">4/4</hi>), hence giving it the name <title>Anonymus Sangallensis</title>. In two of the manuscripts this text is immediately followed by the <title>De astronomia more christiano</title>. Le Bourdellès discovered the two texts in other manuscripts, the oldest being <ref type="altMs" target="Valenciennes_BM_343.xml">Valenciennes, BM, Ms 343</ref>, and so argued that they were composed in a scriptorium in Northern France, and more particularly Corbie.</p>
            <p>Incipit: Herodius dicit helicem licaonis fuisse filiam ...</p>
            <p>Explicit: ... absides eius ultima in capricorno est.</p>
